Posted @withrepost • @m_magazine Disponible demain, un numéro Spécial Iran de M Le magazine du Monde. Le 16 septembre, date de la mort de la jeune Mahsa Amini, arrêtée par la police des mœurs pour « tenue inappropriée », est née une révolte que beaucoup perçoivent comme une révolution. Sur les réseaux sociaux, puisque la censure empêche une couverture médiatique classique, photos et vidéos témoignent du mouvement en cours. Les images de femmes et de filles enlevant leur voile, coupant leurs mèches et allant tête nue sont devenues virales. Ainsi, le monde a pu voir les protestations s’étendre, entendre le beau slogan de « Femme, vie, liberté » résonner dans les rues de Téhéran, d’Ispahan ou de Saqqez, découvrir le visage des manifestants tués et désormais des jeunes hommes exécutés. Malgré tout, ces événements suscitent de grands espoirs. C’est la raison pour laquelle, au moment de choisir le thème de notre traditionnel numéro de fin d’année, l’Iran s’est imposé naturellement.

On Dec. 8, Mohsen Shekari, 23, was the first to be put to death. He was hanged after taking part in protests in Tehran. Four days later, Majid-Reza Rahnavard, also 23, was executed publicly — his body was hanged from a crane in the northeastern city of Mashhad. Like Shekari, he was convicted of "waging war against God," a capital offense.

The executions are Tehran's main response to protests that swept the country since Amini's death, and they signal that Iran's clerical leadership feels it has few options other than brute force to quell the unrest.

Once upon a time, I ate the entire Haftsin lol, my brother understood the assignment as well, everything is just the same. Tehran circa 1993.

This is not an easy Norouz for me, my eyes are constantly wet, and my heart is💔 into pieces, though silent but deep down inside I feel to scream. We’ve lost many beautiful souls and Iranians are mourning. Yet I believe in the magic and the beauty that our ancient Norouz will bring to our homes. Norouz means a new day while life will win over death, and the light will win over darkness.
🖤 Norouz Mobarak 🖤 happy new year 🐇

(7-Seen)
Haftsin is an arrangement of seven symbolic items whose names start with the letter "S/س" (pronounced as "seen"), the 15th letter in the Persian alphabet; "haft" is Persian for "seven". It is traditionally displayed at Norouz, the Persian New Year, which is celebrated on the day of the vernal equinox, marking the beginning of spring 🌸 

1- Sabzeh (سبزه) – wheat, barley, mung bean, or lentil sprouts grown in a dish.
2- Samanu (سمنو) – wheat germ sweet pudding.
3- Senjed (سنجد) – oleaster.
4- Serkeh (سرکه) – vinegar.
5- Seeb (سیب) – apple.
6- Seer (سیر) – garlic.
7- Somagh (سماق) – sumac.

Remember that rejection may not always be about you. When faced with a painful social situation, such as a romantic breakup or exclusion from a group, ask yourself, "What is this situation/person trying to tell me? What can I learn from this?" Managing disrespectful people requires time and understanding to master. Those who seek to anger or hurt us can get under our skin, making it difficult to remain composed. However, this is critical to walking away with our well-being and dignity intact. Giving up is the enemy of creativity, and remember that isolation is an early sign of abuse. Don't allow a toxic group to push you away from your loved ones. In order to build happy, healthy communities, we must hold onto our individuality and value it in one another. You have the right to friendships that fulfill your heart.
I see you and I'm sending you💜

Hamlet, William Shakespeare 🎭

The characters in Hamlet are complex and multi-dimensional, with motivations that are often ambiguous and difficult to understand. Hamlet himself is one of the most fascinating characters in all of literature, with his famous soliloquies revealing his innermost thoughts and struggles. Hamlet deals with timeless themes such as revenge, madness, the nature of reality, and the meaning of life. These themes continue to resonate with readers and audiences. Shakespeare's language in Hamlet is both beautiful and powerful. The play is full of cryptic, metaphorical and puzzling quotes and phrases that have become part of the English language. The play is masterfully structured, with a tightly-woven plot that keeps the audience engaged from start to finish. Hamlet has had a profound influence on literature, theater, art and culture. It has been adapted and reinterpreted countless times, and its impact can still be felt today. I believe that Hamlet is considered one of the greatest plays ever written.
#hamlet

Life in #California for me entails a peaceful and solitary existence. I have come to embrace this tranquility and have learned to find happiness in my own company. One thing I've realized is that choosing a partner out of necessity is often the worst decision, even for those who have immigrated or moved for various reasons. I, too, have made that mistake a few times, but I swiftly changed my course. It still puzzles me why our parents and previous generations, even those just slightly older like a decade, fear the idea of being alone. Perhaps it stems from a fear of self. California has taught me the art of creating a fulfilling life in seclusion, where happiness thrives. Returning to Iran for permanent residency is no longer viable, as I will forever remain a tourist in Tehran. California has become my sanctuary. Throughout the years, as an artist and activist, I have endeavored to shed light on the challenges faced by people in Iran. However, I remain unsure about the practical help we can provide from such a distance, apart from amplifying the voices of the people. We serve as a reflection of your voice, but we cannot go back to live there; and the rest is really in your hands.

‏Living with a heart condition can make life feel dependent on every breath, especially with a history of cardiac arrest at a relatively young age. I can't answer the question of "why did this happen to me?" but I constantly think about the possibility of my breath not returning. Gradually, each time I find myself on the ambulance stretcher and my breath doesn't improve, and they administer nitroglycerin spray under my tongue on the way to the emergency room, I realize that I am living in close proximity to death. While selfish and intoxicated individuals with breaths that smell of alcohol can never comprehend that I have become one with this pain, and we coexist together. I mentioned all of this to say that the only thing that has kept me alive until now has been meditation. The moment I close my eyes and wholeheartedly focus only on the return of my breath.

"Every breath that enters is a source of life, and as it comes out, it brings joy to our existence."

Twenty years ago, while studying at the theater department, my classmate Kaveh @kaveh_tavakoli and I would often take a taxi from the university to an unfamiliar destination and return in complete silence. This ritual (absurd round trip) continued for over two years or maybe even longer. As time went by, I gradually recognized the inherent absurdity and profoundness within that shared silence. Today, I would call it as a silent performance, an ode to the power of silence itself or maybe: The Silence of the Lambs. If I ever have the opportunity to revisit Tehran, it remains my heartfelt wish to recreate that journey, where nothing has changed—neither Kaveh nor the essence of our silent connection.

This morning, I had the privilege of engaging in a thought-provoking and heartfelt conversation with a dear friend from Tehran. We delved deep into the intricate nuances of private and public spaces, exploring the stark differences between our respective cultural perspectives.

It became abundantly clear that what is considered private in Tehran would be deemed a public offense here in LA. The boundaries that define personal space and acceptable behavior vary significantly between our two cultures. This realization left me with a profound sense of sadness, as I recognized the stark disparities and the potential conflicts that can arise when navigating these differences.

Moreover, this discussion brought the notion of "private" and "public" as subjects of scrutiny into the forefront of my mind. It served as a powerful reminder of my younger, more naive self, when I may have settled for the bare minimum and failed to prioritize self-love and respect.

The experience left me with a resolute belief: when someone's private actions encroach upon and harm others in public, it is imperative that those actions are not ignored or dismissed. Instead, they should be openly addressed and resolved, fostering a sense of accountability and justice.

With my years of professional experience in this field, I am inspired to take action. I am hopeful about organizing an IG live event, where we can create a platform for a constructive and inclusive discussion around the complexities of private and public spaces. It would be an opportunity to navigate cultural differences, deepen understanding, and promote empathy among individuals from various backgrounds. Learn to love yourself.💕

I've been working since I was a teenager, and I've never had the luxury of wealthy parents or a desire for a wealthy partner. Living in California without financial support can be quite challenging. The pressures are significant, which is why I had to start working during college. Balancing work and study has been a constant juggling act in my life. I've had to put in a lot of effort to cover essential expenses like rent, food, electric cars, and the cost of my heart medication (All by myself). Lately, this has left me with limited time and energy to focus on other aspects of my life, including my interest in Iran. Being part of the working class in Southern California is no easy feat, and meeting basic needs often feels like a major accomplishment. Sometimes, happiness can feel out of reach. If you can relate to this, I want to remind you to prioritize your mental well-being. Taking care of yourself is crucial, and it's important to remember that every day is an opportunity to improve a little bit more than the day before. Hang in there, and keep pushing forward!
Good night💘
Ps. I am grateful to be in California where proactive measures to address climate change are being taken. However, it is important to acknowledge that life here is undergoing significant transformations.

‏خیلی خسته‌ام و احساس می‌کنم قلمم کم کم داره تموم میشه، اما تا جایی که می‌تونم سعی می‌کنم بنویسم. یه چیز جالبه که بعضی از سلبریتی‌های ایرانی در خارج از کشور (البته برای من شخصا هیچوقت خیلی سلبریتی نبودن) پس از جنبش زن زندگی آزادی، و وکالت به فرقه پهلوی دادن. یکی از اونا حتی پادکستش رو از ۲۰ دقیقه به ۲ ساعت تغییر داد و یکی دیگه موزیک ویدیو جدید ساخت. حتی بعضی هاشون هم نمایشگاه یا کنسرت به اسم "مردم ایران" برگزار کرد. سفرهای ۸۰ روز دور دنیا رو هم add کنین بهش. این ها اونایی هستن که مواضع تند و جنگ‌طلبانه دارن، واقعاً می‌تونن ترسناک به نظر بیان. ولی برای مقابله باهاشون، بهتره از راه‌هایی مثل گپ زدن به صورت مسالمت‌آمیز، دادن اطلاعات منطقی و دلایل منطقی، و حتی شرکت در فعالیت‌های اجتماعی و سیاسی برای تغییر نگرش‌ها استفاده کنیم. سکوت تنها ممکنه مشکلات رو بیشتر کنه و به این افراد اجازه بده که بیشتر کنترل رسانه‌های فارسی رو بگیرن. اینا باید بدونن که ما احمق نیستیم.

This year, I made the decision to reflect on my meditation and share my thoughts with you. First and foremost, I want to express my gratitude for your support. I wouldn’t be where I am today without the love and kindness of those around me, as well as the challenges I faced from those who sought to harm me. Both experiences have contributed to my growth and helped me become a more courageous person. If you find yourself spending this holiday alone and single, like I am, I encourage you to meditate on the things you do have. While we may feel a sense of longing or missing something in our lives, such as in my case, where life before and after having my dog Luna is quite different, meditation can bring us solace. Having gone through many holidays alone after migrating, I can say that being with Luna now fills that void. Those who have dogs understand the rewarding connection we share with these magical creatures, as if they were a gift from heaven on Earth. So, meditate often, knowing that meditation can be a transcendental experience. Remember, you have never truly been alone. let the meditation heal your mind, heart, and soul.
